06127nam a22010095i 9783110220353DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20102010gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002222139  a(OCoLC)1004872558  a(OCoLC)1011439821  a(OCoLC)987921958  a(OCoLC)992454349  a(OCoLC)999367486  a97831102203537 a10.1515/97831102203532doi  a(DE-B1597)36777  a(OCoLC)615622320  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPE179b.M46 2010eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a429/.52221 aMengden, Ferdinand von, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCardinal Numerals :bOld English from a Cross-Linguistic Perspective /cFerdinand von Mengden. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (329 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in English Linguistics [TiEL] ,x1434-3452 ;v670 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book embeds a description and an analysis of the Old English numeral system into a broader, cross-linguistic discussion. It provides a theoretical framework for the study of numerals and numeral systems of natural languages, bridging the gap between recent findings in the cognitive sciences on numeracy and the known typological generalisations on cardinal numerals. The Old English numeral system shows a number of peculiarities not found in the present-day languages of Europe. Its detailed description is therefore an ideal locus for studying the features of linguistic number expressions in terms of their morpho-syntactic properties and of the structure of numeral systems.The approach is innovative in that it combines a detailed analysis of the numeral system with the analysis of the grammatical properties of cardinal numerals. For the description of Old English, the study focuses on aspects of information structure and of referent identification in quantificational constructions. This leads to a novel perspective on the language-internal variation in the agreement patterns between numerals and quantified nouns, allowing the author to test and refine some long standing tenets in the study of numerals and to offer alternative explanations. Rather than seeing numerals as a hybrid word class, the author argues that this variation in the morpho-syntactic behaviour follows identifiable patterns specific to the word class numeral. He accounts for these patterns by positing different, cross-linguistically uniform stages in the emergence of numeral systems, as well as varying degrees of discreteness of the quantified noun. Moreover, the author demonstrates that the constraints determining this variation in Old English have obvious parallels across languages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCardinal numbers. 0aComparative linguistics. 0aEnglish languageyOld English, ca. 450-1100xNumerals. 0aHistorical linguistics. 0aNumeration. 4aEnglisch /Sprache. 4aHistorische Linguistik. 4aTypologie /Sprache. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aEnglish /Language.  aHistorical Linguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Linguistics and Semiotics  2000-2014 (EN)z978311023845708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2010z9783110233544oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES